<section id="research">
    <h2>Groundbreaking Research</h2>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>Core Discovery</h3>
        <blockquote>
            "We proved that heart disease can be reversed through intensive lifestyle changes alone - without drugs or surgery. After a year on our program, patients showed actual regression of coronary atherosclerosis. The body wants to heal if we just stop doing what's causing the problem."
        </blockquote>
    </div>

    <h3>The Landmark Study</h3>
    <p>Dr. Ornish's randomized controlled trial, published in The Lancet in 1990, showed:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Reversal of atherosclerosis:</strong> Actual shrinkage of coronary artery blockages</li>
        <li><strong>Improved blood flow:</strong> Better perfusion to heart muscle</li>
        <li><strong>Reduced symptoms:</strong> Less chest pain and shortness of breath</li>
        <li><strong>No surgery needed:</strong> Many patients avoided bypass surgery</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Long-Term Follow-Up</h3>
    <p>Five-year follow-up studies showed:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Continued improvement in treatment group</li>
        <li>Continued progression in control group</li>
        <li>91% reduction in cardiac events</li>
        <li>Sustained benefits with sustained adherence</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Telomere Research</h3>
    <p>More recent research from Dr. Ornish showed his lifestyle program can actually lengthen telomeres - the caps on chromosomes that shorten with age - suggesting lifestyle changes may slow biological aging.</p>
</section>

<section id="program">
    <h2>The Ornish Program</h2>

    <p>The Ornish Program for Reversing Heart Disease has four components:</p>

    <h3>1. Nutrition</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Whole-foods, plant-based diet</li>
        <li>Very low fat (approximately 10% of calories)</li>
        <li>No added oils or animal products (except egg whites and nonfat dairy optional)</li>
        <li>Emphasis on vegetables, fruits, whole grains, legumes</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>2. Exercise</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Moderate aerobic exercise</li>
        <li>Walking 30-60 minutes per day</li>
        <li>Strength training</li>
        <li>Flexibility exercises</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>3. Stress Management</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Yoga and stretching</li>
        <li>Meditation and relaxation techniques</li>
        <li>Deep breathing exercises</li>
        <li>Progressive relaxation</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>4. Love and Support</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Group support sessions</li>
        <li>Communication skills training</li>
        <li>Emotional intimacy</li>
        <li>Community connection</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="warning-box">
        <h3>Different Approach</h3>
        <p>Dr. Ornish's very low-fat plant-based approach differs significantly from the low-carb/metabolic health approach advocated by other experts on this site. Both approaches have shown benefits in research, and the optimal diet may vary by individual. The common ground is: whole foods, avoiding processed foods, and intensive lifestyle change.</p>
    </div>
</section>

